## ðŸ”— **Clinical Ontology vs Terminology - Summary**

### ðŸ“š Key Definitions
- **Terminology:** A standardized **list of codes and terms** (e.g., SNOMED CT, ICD-10, LOINC, RxNorm) created by external standards bodies.
- **Ontology:** A **structured model** that defines **concepts, relationships, and meaning** within a clinical or business domain. Itâ€™s more than just a list â€” itâ€™s a **knowledge graph**.
- **Custom Ontology Model (COM):** A **homegrown, internal ontology** created by an organization to act as its **single source of truth** for clinical concepts, linking to external terminologies as needed.

---

### ðŸ”„ **Mapping**
Mapping = translation between terminologies or between a terminology and your custom ontology.
- Example: **SNOMED "Type 2 diabetes" maps to ICD-10 "E11.9".**
- Mappings can be:
    - **1-to-1** (clean match)
    - **1-to-many** (more than one valid target, requiring logic to choose)
    - **Many-to-1** (several detailed concepts collapse into one code)
    - **No match** (gap requiring manual handling)

---

### ðŸ”¥ Why COM is Powerful
âœ… Acts as a **neutral hub** connecting all incoming data (claims, EHR, public health feeds, etc.) into a single **canonical representation**.
âœ… Allows you to store **clinical relationships** â€” e.g., diabetes â†’ needs retinal exam, diabetes â†’ treated by metformin.
âœ… Handles **non-1-to-1 mappings** gracefully by attaching **business rules** to decide how to translate.
âœ… Supports **both clinical and financial needs** (quality, risk adjustment, care management, etc.).
âœ… Supports **multi-domain coverage** â€” conditions, medications, procedures, labs, allergies, immunizations, and more.

---

### ðŸ—‚ï¸ External Terminologies â€” What Each One Covers

| Domain | Common Terminologies |
|---|---|
| **Conditions (diagnoses)** | SNOMED CT (clinical), ICD-10 (billing) |
| **Medications** | RxNorm (prescribed), NDC (dispensed) |
| **Labs & Vitals** | LOINC |
| **Procedures** | CPT (billing), SNOMED CT (clinical) |
| **Immunizations** | CVX |
| **Allergies** | RxNorm (drugs), SNOMED (non-drug allergens) |
| **Social History, Family History** | SNOMED CT (often) |

